<title>CTO : Lazy Evaluation</title><link rel="alternate" type="application/rss+xml" title="Recent Changes" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050414222638/http://cliki.tunes.org/recent-changes.rdf"><link rel="stylesheet" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050414222638cs_/http://cliki.tunes.org/admin/cliki.css"></head><body><div id="banner"><a title="CTO" class="logo" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050414222638/http://cliki.tunes.org/">CTO</a> <span>CLiki for the TUNES project</span></div><div id="navbar"><a class="internal" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050414222638/http://cliki.tunes.org/index">Home</a> <a class="internal" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050414222638/http://cliki.tunes.org/Recent%20Changes">Recent Changes</a> <a class="internal" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050414222638/http://cliki.tunes.org/CLiki">About CLiki</a> <a class="internal" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050414222638/http://cliki.tunes.org/Text%20Formatting">Text Formatting</a> <a class="internal" onclick="if(name=window.prompt('New page name ([A-Za-z0-9 ])')) document.location='https://web.archive.org/web/20050414222638/http://cliki.tunes.org/edit/'+name ;return false;" href="/web/20050414222638/http://cliki.tunes.org/">Create New Page</a></div><div id="main"><h1>Lazy Evaluation</h1>The <a class="internal" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050414222638/http://cliki.tunes.org/term">term</a> for a strategy<a class="internal" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050414222638/http://cliki.tunes.org/edit/strategy">?</a> to evaluate objects only when one is sure they are useful or needed, and not before.

<p>Lazy evaluation allows avoiding lots of (possibly infinite) computations, while greatly simplifying the way to code <a class="internal" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050414222638/http://cliki.tunes.org/high-level">high-level</a> programs.

<p>One disadvantage is that evaluation order is not inherently specifiable; an extra notation is usually required. Another disadvantage is that computational suspensions must be kept around conservatively until explicitly worked out that they are not needed.
